ðŸŒ  The Personal Network Building OS


    Good Mythical Morning

Your network is like HomeTree from Avatar. 

It's the web of connections in your life.


76 writers? 19 Portuguese  speakers in Sao Paulo?  13 e-friends from Hong Kong?

Small groups of friendships from the past 3 months.

Need writing resources?  76 friends to help.

Language partners in Sao Paulo/Hong Kong?  No problem.


& when you create something useful,  you have a support system to share it with.


The OS:

It's a habit, not a 1-time project.


What you need:

  • Database (your HomeTree)
  • Pool of people
  • A value-add

Your  database  stores contacts & notes in a tag-able, searchable way. 

The brain is bad at remembering things.  It's polite to remember.

I use Dex . Their  web extension pulls info into your db automatically. It looks like this:

Find a pool of people w/ a shared interest.

If knitting, find the online knitting club.

Love an author? Check the author's social followers.

Message a handful of people each day.

Read into each person's projects & interests.

Find the genuine overlap between your passions & theirs.

Then, inquire about their stuff.

Invest time, thoughts, or energy in what they're doing .

Be intentional. Be considerate. Be  thoughtful.

Then,  be helpful .

Offer:   your skills,  resources, advice ,  feedback, etc.


In each message:

  • Connect over shared interest
  • Invest in their work
  • Offer to help (add value)


This is the bedrock for building strong relationships.

The goal with each message is to move each person in a net-positive direction.

Do this everyday & watch your network of friendships flourish.


What not to do:

  • Send mass automated messages
  • Not personalize
  • Ask for something

I've made these mistakes.

Volume is tempting, but real relationships don't scale.

& they aren't supposed to.

Prioritize depth over width.


Tools:

Dex

  • Best personal CRM & database (imo)
  • The founder Kevin's a rockstar 

Loom

  • Send personalized video message responses over email

Lunchclub  (yes, again)

  • Meet amazing people in your niche

VideoAsk

  • 2 way video conversations with every person that lands on your site

ðŸ”Ž  An SEO Optimization Checklist


    Giphy

To get your beautiful creations in front of people, you need to know some SEO.

Write for readers first, then optimize for search engines.

I'm no expert, but I'm curious. 

A spongy pupil, if you will. 

Here's what I learned  from Neil Patel's SEO course.


11 1-liners to Improve SEO:

1.  Add your domain to Google's Search Console ( how to )

2. Generate a xml site map & submit it to Google Search Console ( how to )

  • I use Webflow, they generate it for me.

3. Add  SSL cert

  • Https versus http
  • Done through web host  or site builder

4. Compress images before adding to your site ( free compressor )

5. Use alt tags to describe images

6. Link your pages to each other internally

  • Makes it easier for search engines to crawl your site
  • ~3-4 internal links/1500 words is solid

7. In general, shorter URLs are better

8. Don't put dates in URLs

9. Use max of 2 folders in URLs

  • Aka 2 backslashes
  • rickcarabba.com/projects/learnspanish is 2 folders.

10. Set Open Graph image, title, & description

  • This is what's shown on social/sms when someone shares your pages
  • Set through your site builder (webflow, wordpress, ghost, wix, etc.)
11. Set title tag & meta description
  • What's shown on search engines when someone looks up your pages
  • Set through your site builder (webflow, wordpress, ghost, wix, etc.)
  • Make title tag aligned with your H1 on the page


I didn't mention keywords. 

But I plan on writing on them once I have a strategy that works. 

You can vote for keyword strategy below : )


Tools:

Ubersuggest's SEO Audit Tool
  • Enter your domain, get a free report on how to improve your site
Browseo
  • See how Google sees your site  (pure HTML, for more technical people)
Free Image Compressor
